Recently, Bux et al.35 used an incremental ball milling process to address the problem of Mg agglomeration. In this process, small amount of Mg (200–500 mg) was added into a stoichiometric amount of Si and Bi and ball milled for intervals of less than 1 h. An additional 200 to 500 mg of increments of Mg were added and ball milled until the correct stoichiometry was achieved. The reaction could be could be completed within 8 h depending on the amount of materials. The scanning electron microscope (SEM) shows the powders are made up of mostly large aggregates ranging from 50 nm to micron sizes (Fig. 4a), while transmission electron microscope (TEM) imaging shows smaller grains size (on the order of 30 nm) (Fig. 4b). The synthesized powders were than compacted into pellets via hot pressing for thermoelectric transport measurements. A maximum ZT value of 0.7 was obtained for the samples with optimal Bi concentration (0.15%) (Fig. 4c). The lower ZT obtained in Mg2Si compared to Mg2(SiSn) reported in Ref. 24 is mainly caused by the higher lattice thermal conductivity (κL\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
